INSERT INTO `ingredient` VALUES (1,'Acid Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Acid malt contains acids from natural lactic acids.  Used by German brewers to adjust malt PH without chemicals to adhere to German purity laws.  Also enhances the head retention. '),(2,'Lager Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Very light lager malt used to make Pilsners, Lagers and other light beers.  May be used as a base malt.'),(3,'Lemon',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(4,'Light Dry Extract',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Pale dry malt extract for general purpose use.\nUse as base or to increase gravity of any full bodied ale or lager.'),(5,'Lime',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(6,'Loganberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Cross between raspberry and blackberry flavors.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(7,'Lychee',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and cube or crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(8,'Lyle\'s Golden Syrup',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Liquid Invert Sugar.  Used to increase alcohol and lighten the beer without alterning flavor.  Used in Belgian ales and some English ales.'),(9,'Maltodextrin',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Used to add mouthfeel to a beer.  It is marked as non-fermentable as it is usually 97% unfermentable sugars.'),(10,'Mango',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(11,'Maple Syrup',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'If added during the boil it will add a dry, woodsy flavor. If added at bottling, the smooth maple flavor comes through.  Used for maple ales, porters, browns.'),(12,'Melanoiden Malt',1,2,0.453592,3,0.00,0,'Aromatic malt from Banberg, Germany.  Promotes a full flavor and rounds off beer color. Promotes deep red color and malty flavor.'),(13,'Melanoidin (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Red colored malt that improved head retention and stability.  Used in red lagers, ales, dark beers.  Intense red colour and malty aroma.'),(14,'Mild Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Also called \"English Mild\" - a light specialty malt used in Brown Ales'),(15,'Milk Sugar (Lactose)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Not fermentable, so it adds lasting sweetness. Lactose can be added to lend  sweetness to Sweet Stouts and Porters.'),(16,'Molasses',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Imparts a strong, sweet flavor.  Used primarily in stouts and porters.'),(17,'Munich I (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Light Munich malt.  May be used as a base for many German beer styles.  Fest beers, bocks, ales. Enhances malty flavour and aroma'),(18,'Munich II (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Darker Munich Malt.  Used as a base malt in many German beer styles.  Fest beers, bocks and ales.  Enhances malt flavour and aroma'),(19,'Munich Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Malty-sweet flavor characteristic and adds a reddish amber color to the beer.\nDoes not contribute signficantly to body or head retention.\nUse for: Bock, Porter, Marzen, Oktoberfest beers'),(20,'Munich Malt - 10L',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Malty-sweet flavor characteristic and adds a slight orange color to the beer.\nDoes not contribute signficantly to body or head retention.\nUse for: Bock, Porter, Marzen, Oktoberfest beers'),(21,'Munich Malt - 20L',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Malty-sweet flavor characteristic and adds a orange to deep orange color to the beer.\nDoes not contribute signficantly to body or head retention.\nUse for: Bock, Porter, Marzen, Oktoberfest beers'),(22,'Naranjilla',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(23,'Oats, Flaked',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Adds body, mouth feel and head retention to the beer\nUsed in oatmeal stouts and porters\nAdds substantial protein haze to light beers\nProtein rest recommended unless flakes are pregelatinized'),(24,'Oats, Malted',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Malted oats.  Adds body, mouth feel and head retention to the beer  Creates chill haze in lighter beers, so is primarily used in dark ones.\n'),(25,'Orange',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(26,'Organic Concord Grape Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Organic Just Concord Grape\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation. SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n'),(27,'Organic Cranberry Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Organic Just Cranberry\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation. SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n'),(28,'Organic Pomegranate Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Organic Just Pomegranate\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation. SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n'),(29,'Organic Prune Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Organic Just Prune\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation. SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n'),(30,'Organic Tart Cherry Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Organic Just Tart Cherry\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation. SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n'),(31,'Kiwi',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(32,'Invert Sugar',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Used to increase starting gravity and also as an adjunct for some Belgian and English ales.'),(33,'Honeydew Melon',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(34,'Honey Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Intensely sweet - adds a sweet malty flavor sometimes associated with honey.  Also called Brumalt.'),(35,'Extra Light Dry Extract',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Very light color dry malt extract for general purpose use.\nUse as base or to increase gravity of any ale or lager.'),(36,'Figs',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(37,'Grapefruit',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(38,'Grapes - Concord',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Concord are sweet grapes made for juice, but not really suitable for wine making.  Use an appropriate wine grape instead if making wine.  Generally you want to crush and destem before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(39,'Grits',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Imparts a corn or grain taste.  Mash required. Used to increase gravity of American lagers.'),(40,'Guava',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(41,'Honey',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Generic honey - usually Clover honey is sold in US supermarkets.  Will generally lighten body and flavor when used in beer as it is highly fermentable.  Modern methods add honey directly to the primary to avoid boiling away aroma and flavor.  Some varieties have additional flavors (see the Honey Varietals add-on).'),(42,'Honey - Acacia',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Acacia honey is made from the nectar of black locust plants.  Very sweet with a mild delicate floral taste.  High fructose content, often used therapeutically.'),(43,'Honey - Alfalfa',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Alfalfa is a light, delicate honey made from bees feeding on alfalfa.  In meads is delicate and fairly clean in flavor.'),(44,'Honey - Apple Blossom',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Light to medium amber in color and a hint of apple in the aroma.'),(45,'Honey - Avacado',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'A flavorful, earthy honey made by bees foraging on avacado trees.  Dark amber color. Hints of molasses and sorghum, a rich, full bodied flavorful honey.'),(46,'Honey - Basswood',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Made from Basswood blossoms in North America. One of the few light colored honeys that has a strong biting flavor.  Woody scents and a strong biting flavor.'),(47,'Honey - Blackberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Medium light in color and very sweet.  Some fruity character comes thorugh from the blackberries.'),(48,'Honey - Blueberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Deep flavor profile from bees foraging on blueberry bushes.  Mid color range with a slightly fruity character.'),(49,'Pale Ale Malt, Northwestern (Great Western)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Northwest Pale Ale Malt (2.6-3.0°L)\nA slightly darker base malt than our Premium 2-Row, our Northwest Pale Ale Malt is produced from well-modified, Western-grown 2-Row barley, with a kilning regimen based closely on traditional British Pale Ale malting practices. Contributes a malty complexity to beer flavor and aroma. Excellent in American Pale Ales and American versions of British beer styles. \n\n'),(50,'Honey - Buckwheat',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Probably the strongest and darkets of varietal honey. Dark in color. Strong molasses finish and capable of making \"single malt\" meads.  Can be musty and earthy in aroma. Some eastern varieties can take on a \"barnyard\" character though western US versions are less so.\n\nThe strong flavor can overwhelm/conflict with many fruits and spices, so select complementatry flavor combos.'),(51,'Honey - Clover',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'The most common variety sold in supermarkets with a huge annual production.  Delicate and relatively neutral in flavor.  Some variation due to the large production area. '),(52,'Honey - Cranberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Mild and fruity in flavor with a tart aftertaste.  Medium amber color.'),(53,'Honey - Eucalyptus',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'A rich distinctive honey made from bees foraging Eucalyptus trees in Australia. A full body honey with hints of Eucalyptus.'),(54,'Honey - Fireweed',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Fireweed comes from a perennial herb grown in the Pacific North West US.  Sweet, complex, buttery taste.  Buttery finish.'),(55,'Honey - Heather',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Slightly bitter with an aftertaste of burnt caramel.  Dark amber in color.'),(56,'Honey - Mesquite',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Light, delicate and hints of mesquite flavor, but not smoky.  Makes a nice single variety mead if you enjoy the flavor of the honey.'),(57,'Honey - Orange Blossom',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Orange blossom honey is a favorite of fruit mead makers.  A delicate fragrance, sweet and clean fermenting.  Fragrant, light, heady, slight hints of orange blossom.'),(58,'Honey - Pumpkin Blossom',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Made once a year from the nectar of Pumpkin Blossoms in early fall.  Dark, amber colored with a light floral fragrance.  Works well when contrasted with spicy foods and spices.  It does not taste like pumpkin pie, however.'),(59,'Honey - Raspberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Raspberry honey from the white blossoms of the raspberry bush.  Amber in color, mellow finish and hints of raspberry.  Slightly fruity and pairs well with vanilla.'),(60,'Honey - Sage',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Sage honey is made primarily in California.  It is heavy bodied but has a mild flavor.  It is often blended with other honeys as it does not easily granulate.'),(61,'Honey - Sourwood',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Sourwood honey is sweet, light colored and dlicate.  It has a caramel or buttery flavor to it and a pleasant buttery aftertaste.'),(62,'Honey - Sunflower',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Distinctive floral aromas.  Easily crystalizes.  Light to medium amber in color.'),(63,'Honey - Tupelo',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'The champagne of honey.  Highly prized by many mead makers. Tupelo honey is light amber with a slightly greenish color and a pear-like hoppy aroma. Delicate, mild, buttery, floral.  Works well with many fruits.'),(64,'Honey - Wildflower',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Wildflower bees capture nectars from a wide variety of trees, shrubs, and flowers.  Some variability due to wide range of production.  Deep, rich, and not as sweet as clover honey.  Some examples really capture wild character of flora used.\n\nQuite a bit of variability in production - so sample before using.'),(65,'Honey - Chesnut',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Produced primarily in Italy from the blossoms of chesnut trees.  Has a unique aroma and slightly bitter flavor.  Amber in color, and only mildly sweet.\n'),(66,'Pale Liquid Extract',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Unhopped pale liquid extract.\nUse as a base malt for any ale or lager.'),(67,'Pale Malt (2 Row) Bel',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Base malt for all beer styles\nHigher potential yield than US, English 