eze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(123,'Rice Extract Syrup',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Used like other rice adjuncts in American and Japenes lagers to provide a dry, clean taste and light body.  Adds gravity without changing body or flavor substantially.  Use in place of corn sugar in small quantities.'),(124,'Rice Hulls',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Hulls are introduced to improve the speed of lautering when making high gravity or high adjunct beers.\nHulls are neutral in flavor, body and color, and are inert\nGood for wheat beers, Wits, and others that have high protein mashes.'),(125,'Rice, Flaked',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Used to add fermentables without increasing body or flavor.\nProduces a milder, less grainy tasting beer.\nExamples: American lagers, Bohemian lagers, Pilsners'),(126,'Roasted Barley',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Roasted at high temperature to create a burnt, grainy, coffee like flavor.\nImparts a red to deep brown color to beer, and very strong roasted flavor.\nUse 2-4% in Brown ales to add a nutty flavor, or 3-10% in Porters and Stouts for coffee flavor.'),(127,'Rye Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Adds a dry, crisp character to the beer.  \nYields a deep red color, and a distinctive rye flavor\nMust limit to 10-15% fo the mash as it tends to produce \"stuck\" mashes.'),(128,'Rye Malt (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Rye malt for rye style beers.  Up to 50% may be used in some rye styles.  Adds distinctive rye flavor and aroma.'),(129,'Rye, Flaked',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Imparts a dry, crisp rye flavor to rye beers.  Can be easier to mash than raw rye.'),(130,'Sinamar (Wyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'A unique coloring agent in liquid form.  Schwartz beer, colour adjustment.Roast malt beer extract.'),(131,'Smoked Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Malt that has been smoked over an open fire.\nCreates a distinctive \"smoked\" flavor and aroma.\nUsed primarily for German Rauchbier but can also be added to Brown Ales and Porters.'),(132,'Smoked Malt (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Smoked flavor and aroma base malt.  Used in smoked ales, lagers and wheat beers, primarily German styles.'),(133,'Plum',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(134,'Dewberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  A close relative of Blackberries. Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(135,'Dememera Sugar',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Dark, unrefined brown sugar that contains molasses and other dark impurities.  Great for brown ales and porters.  Adds slight sweetness and smooth character.'),(136,'Dates',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(137,'Apple Juice - Slippery Cider',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - Medium body.  Medium to high acidity.  Not much noticeable tannin presence except that the flavor seems lightly nutty and spiced.\n\nOverall Impression - A good cider but not exceptional.  Interesting in subtle ways.  Could benefit from higher gravity or more tannins. Total tannins=0.15%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/slippery-cider-apple-cider-evaluation'),(138,'Apple Juice - Smokehouse',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider -Medium body and acidity.  The residual sweetness is more noticeable than it was for most of the ciders we tested (we won\'t speculate as to the reason since there are a number of possible explanations).  Not much noticeable tannin except for a hint of astringency on the finish.  \nOverall Impression - Very drinkable.  Very good.  Well balanced on its own and great for a base.  Total tannins=0.15%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/smokehouse-apple-cider-evaluation'),(139,'Apple Juice - Snow',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Variable sized apple also known as Fameuse.  Bi-color green and red.  Originated from plantings by French settlers in Quebec. For cider - Soft mouthfeel and a bit thin.  Mildly tart with some lingering acidity.  Little to no noticeable tannins.\nOverall Impression - A light, refreshing cider.  A good cider base with balanced acidity that would blend well with a bittersweet.Total tannins=0.06%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/snow-apple-cider-evaluation'),(140,'Apple Juice - Stump',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - Light to medium body.  Low to medium acidity.  Mild apple flavor.  Little to no noticeable tannins.\n\nOverall Impression - Unremarkable, but not bad.  Total tannins=0.10%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/stump'),(141,'Apple Juice - Swiss Limbertwig',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - Medium body.  Medium to high acidity.  Mild bitterness and astringency fills out the cider. Overall Impression - Nice, balanced.  Good all around.  Total tannins=0.20%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/swiss-limbertwig-apple-cider-evaluation'),(142,'Apple Juice - Tremlett\'s Bitter',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Intense, well known English cider apple very high in tannins.  For cider -Unfortunately we did not have enough juice from Tremlett\'s Bitter to create a single varietal cider for further testing. Total tannins=1.20%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/tremletts-bitter'),(143,'Apple Juice - Wisconsin Russet',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Also known as Jeidy Russet.  For cider - Full body.  High acidity.  Rich, puckery fruit flavors.  Long, mouth-watering finish.  Mild bitterness and astringency rounds out the cider.\n\nOverall Impression -  Very good cider.  From it\'s cold Wisconsin home, this apple produces a surprising, tart fruit punch that brings memories of warmer weather and can carry one away to a bright, tropical place even on a wintry night. Total tannins=0.25%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/wisconsin-russet-apple-cider-evaluation'),(144,'Apple Juice - Wolf River',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'From the banks of the Wolf River in Wisconsin. For cider - Low to medium body.  Classic tart apple flavor.  Little to no noticeable tannins.  Overall Impression - Good base apple with a straight-forward tart apple flavor.  Would be enjoyable on a hot day when floating down the Wolf River. Total tannins=0.11%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/new-page'),(145,'Apple Juice - Yarlington Mill',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Traditional English Cider apple.  For cider - Full body.  Rich.  Slight residual sweetness is noticeable with the low acidity.  Pleasant tannins - lightly drying and slight bitterness.  Notes of oak, spiced rum, molasses, anise.\n\nOverall Impression - Wow!  Definitely a stand out cider apple.  Wish more ciders tasted like that. Total tannins=0.20%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/yarlington-mill'),(146,'Apples - Gala',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit - gala apples.  More suited to eating than cider making. Generally you want to crush or finely dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(147,'Apricot',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit - Apricots.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and finely dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(148,'Aromatic Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Provides a very strong malt flavor and aroma to your beer.'),(149,'Banana',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit - Bananas. Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and dice before use. Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(150,'Barley Hulls',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Hulls are introduced to improve the speed of lautering when making high gravity or high adjunct beers.\nHulls are neutral in flavor, body and color, and are inert\nGood for wheat beers, Wits, and others that have high protein mashes.'),(151,'Apple Juice - Shiawassee',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - Moderate, soft mouthfeel that gives way to full and long lasting acidity.  Little noticeable tannins. \n\nOverall Impression – Great for adding aromatics and acidity to a blend, a little too acidic on its own. Total tannins=0.10%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/shiawassee'),(152,'Barley, Flaked',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Adds significant body to Porters and Stouts.  High haze producing protein prevents use in light beers.'),(153,'Barley, Torrefied',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Raw barley that has been \"popped\" open to open kernels\nUsed in place of raw barley for faster conversion and higher yields.\nHigh in haze producing protein'),(154,'Biscuit Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Use for English ales, brown ales and porters.\nAdds a biscuit like flavor and aroma.\nCan be used as a substitute for toasted malt.'),(155,'Black (Patent) Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Dark color and dry roasted flavor characteristic of Stouts and Porters\nUse for: Coloring in small amounts, or flavoring of Stouts and Porters in larger amounts.'),(156,'Black Barley (Stout)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Unmalted barley roasted at high temperature to create a dry, coffee like flavor.\nImparts a sharp acrid flavor characteristic of dry stouts.\nGives \"dryness\" to a stout or porter -- much more so than regular Roasted Barley'),(157,'Black Cherry Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Just Black Cherry\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation.  SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n\nNote - their tart cherry has more tannins and will produce more flavor post-fermentation.'),(158,'Black Currant',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(159,'Black Currant Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Just Black Currant\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation. SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n'),(160,'Blackberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(161,'Blueberry Juice - Knudsen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Knudsen\'s \'Just Blueberry\' juice suitable for use in mead, wine, cider, beer.  Sold in 1 quart jars.  Pasteurized but has no preservatives making it suitable for fermentation. SRM color listed is a rough estimate.\n'),(162,'Boysenberry',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(163,'Brewer\'s Malt, 2-Row, Premium (Great Western)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Premium 2-Row Malt (1.8-2.2°L) \nOur most popular base malt, perfect for all beer styles, especially American ales and lagers. With moderate protein and enzyme levels and a very clean, smooth finish, our Premium 2-Row Malt is ideal for all-malt beers and for mashes containing moderate levels of adjunct. '),(164,'Brown Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Imparts a dry, biscuit flavor. Used in nut brown ales, porters and some Belgian ales.'),(165,'Brown Sugar, Dark',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Imparts a rich sweet flavor. Used in Scottish ales, holiday ales and some old ales.'),(166,'Brown Sugar, Light',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Imparts a rich sweet flavor. Used in Scottish ales, holiday ales and some old ales.'),(167,'Barley, Raw',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Raw, unmalted barley can be used to add body to your beer.  Use in homebrew requires very fine milling combined with a decoction or multi-stage mash.  Performs best when used in small quantities with well modified grains.'),(168,'Brumalt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Dark German malt developed to add malt flavor of Alt, Marzen and Oktoberfest beers. Helps create authentic maltiness without having to do a decoction mash.  Rarely available for homebrewers.'),(169,'Apple Juice - Russet Cow',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Crunchy medium size apple.  For cider - Medium body.  High acidity.  Long, tart finish.  Little to no noticeable tannins.\n\nOverall Impression - Perhaps too one dimensional to stand on its own but could be used to add acidity to a blend. Total tannins=0.06%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/russet-cow'),(170,'Apple Juice - Razor Russet',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Similar to Golden Delicious. For cider - Medium body.  Alcohol bite fills it out.  Nice acidity level - not too high, not too low.  Little to no noticeable tannins.  Pleasant apple/grape flavor.\n\nOverall Impression - A very good cider on its own.  It\'s attractive, and everything is in nice balance (except that it lacks tannins). Total tannins=0.08%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/razor-russet-apple-cider-evaluation'),(171,'Acidulated (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Used in Germany to lower PH levels without resorting to chemicals.  Lowers mash pH levels, lightens color, improves flavor stability.'),(172,'Amber Dry Extract',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Amber colored dry malt extract, for general purpose use.\nUse in any medium to dark colored beer.\nExamples: Ales, Marzens, Amber Ale, India Pale Ale'),(173,'Amber Liquid Extract',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Unhopped amber color liquid extract.\nUse as a base malt for any Ale.\nExamples: Amber ale, India Pale Ale, Munich style, Marzen, Bock'),(174,'Amber Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Roasted specialty malt used in some English browns, milds and old ales to add color and a biscuit taste.  Intense flavor - so limit use. Low diastatic power so must be mashed with well modified malts.'),(175,'Apple Juice  - Early Windsor',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Known as Alkmene in Germany where it was initially grown.  For cider - Medium to light body.  Medium to high acidity.  Long tart finish.  Slightly drying but otherwise no noticeable tannins..  Total tannins=0.11%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/earlywindsor'),(176,'Apple Juice - Black Gilliflower',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Cider making variety.  Medium to medium large. Full bodied, balanced, sharp cider apple with a pleasant bite.  Notable but mild tannins, some woody notes. Wine like.  Total tannins=0.14%\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/black-gilliflower-apple-cider-evaluation'),(177,'Apple Juice - Blenheim Orange',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - low in aroma, tart, highly acidic with some astringency.  Somewhat tart on its own but may be a good apple for a blend.  Total tannins = 0.12%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/blenheim-orange'),(178,'Apple Juice - Carrol',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - medium to light in body, medium acidity, a mild tart apple.  Slightly more astringent than low tannin would expect.  Total tannins=0.08%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/carroll'),(179,'Apple Juice - Christmas Pearmain',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - Medium to light body.  Moderate to slightly high acidity with a long finish.  Little in the way of tannins.  Good cider base, straightforward.  Total tannins=0.11%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/christmas-pearmain-apple-cider-evaluation'),(180,'Apple Juice - Coopers Market',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider -Medium body.  Dominated by tart, lingering green apple acidity, somewhat biting but not overly harsh.  Little noticeable tannins.  Total tannins=0.07%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/coopers-market-apple-cider-evaluation'),(181,'Apple Juice - Cortland',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Popular eating apple bred in NY in the late 1800s.  For cider -Low to medium body.  Moderate acidity - starts mild then builds and fades slowly.  Little to no noticeable tannins.  Mild sour apple flavor.  Not an exciting cider, but may work well in a blend. Total tannins=0.06%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/cortland-apple-cider-evaluation'),(182,'Apple Juice - Egremont Russet',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - Medium body, noticeable alcohol.  Moderate to high acidity, like tart cherry juice.  Long finish.  Little noticeable tannins. Total tannins=0.12%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/egremont-russet-apple-cider-evaluation'),(183,'Apple Juice - Gala',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Popular Eating Apple.  For cider - Straight forward cider flavor.  Medium body.  Medium to low acidity.  Little to no tannins.  Simple.  Clean, very easy to drink.  Nothing exciting but not bad. Total tannins=0.05%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/gala-apple-cider-evaluation'),(184,'Apple Juice - Garfield',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'An apple grafted from a tree at the Garfield Farm Museum in LaFox, Illinois. Excellent cider.  Nicely balanced.  Intriguing aroma and full flavor.  Intriguing story to the apple as well.Total tannins=0.16%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/garfield'),(185,'Apple Juice - Red Cortland',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Large, very similar to a regular Cortland, just a bit redder.  For cider - Low to medium body.  Light at first with a tart, lingering finish.  Medium acidity overall.  Little to no noticeable tannins.\n\nOverall Impression - Very drinkable cider.  Fine for a base apple.  Might be nice to have a higher gravity apple to fill it out, but it\'s nonetheless enjoyable as a light, refreshing cider. Total tannins=0.06%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/red-cortland-apple-cider-evaluation'),(186,'Apple Juice - Gloster',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider - Initial burst of flavor and gushing, juicy mouthfeel that fades to a lingering astringency.  Moderate acidity and notable \"bite\" of alcohol.  The astringent finish suggests more tannins than testing revealed. Good, full flavored cider with nice balance of acids.  It stands up fairly well on its own or could be used to add some oomph to a weaker cider. Total tannins=0.12%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/gloster-apple-cider-evaluation'),(187,'Apple Juice - Haralson',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Slightly tart apple from Minnesota.  For cider - Light to medium body.  Medium to slightly high acidity.  A hint of something funky  - perhaps something wasn\'t perfectly clean and happy during the fermentation (we don\'t claim to be perfect).  Little to no noticeable tannins. Probably could have been better (blame the cider maker).  Even so, it was a little thin.  Could be used to add some acidity to a blend. Total tannins=0.10%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/haralson-apple-cider-evaluation'),(188,'Apple Juice - Hauer Pippin',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'For cider -Mellow, straight-forward apple flavor.  Unassuming on first sip but a long, lingering finish.  Moderate acidity.  Little to no noticeable tannins. Light, subtle, and drinkable.  Unadorned apple flavor and aroma.  Would make a fine backdrop for blending with almost any apple. Total tannins=0.08%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/hauer-pippin-apple-cider-evaluation'),(189,'Apple Juice - Honeycrisp',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Popular eating variety.  For cider - Medium to light body.  Moderate acidity.  Little to no noticeable tannins. Nothing exciting but not bad.  Would make a good, neutral base for blending with other apples. Mild apple flavor. Total tannins=0.07%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/honeycrisp-apple-cider-evaluation'),(190,'Apple Juice - Horneburger Pancake',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'From Northern Germany.  For cider - Medium body.  Medium to high acidity.  Subtle but noticeable bitterness.  Little astringency.  Long, tart finish. Makes a pretty good cider, would add some acidity, unique aroma, and subtle bitterness to a blend.Total tannins=0.13%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/horneburger-pancake'),(191,'Apple Juice - Lady Sweet',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Mild flavor.  For cider - Low acidity.  Light mouthfeel.  Mild apple skin flavor.  Little to no noticeable tannins.  Mild cider overall.  Nothing remarkable but nothing bad.  Easy to drink.  Could mellow an overly sharp cider. Total tannins=0.07%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/lady-sweet'),(192,'Apple Juice - London Pippen',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Crisp with a pleasant apple flavor but not very juicy.  For cider - Fresh apple flavor.  Refreshing and balanced.  Medium body, medium acidity, little to no tannin.\n\nOverall Impression – Enjoyable cider.  Classic apple flavor. Total tannins=0.07%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/london-pippen-apple-cider-evaluation'),(193,'Apple Juice - Macintosh',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Popular eating apple.  For cider - Medium body.  Fresh, tart apple flavor.  Moderate to strong acidity. Overall Impression – This common eating apple makes a pleasant cider with the familiar tart apple flavor of a Mac.  Great base apple.  Could make for a world class cider if blended with a bittersweet.  Total tannins=0.11%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/macintosh-apple-cider-evaluation'),(194,'Apple Juice - Marin Oufroy',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'French Cider Apple.  For cider - Full mouthfeel.  Sherry-like.  Noticeable sweetness with the low acidity.  Soft tannins.  Woody.  Baked apple, raisin.  Alcohol finish. Overall Impression - Excellent cider.  Rich, complex.  Highly recommended. Total tannins=0.31%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/marin-oufroy-apple-cider-evaluation'),(195,'Apple Juice - Minkler',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Heirloom apple from the 1800s.  For cider - Moderate mouthfeel.  Little acidity.  Noticeable tannins, mildly bitter and astringent.  Slightly woody, leathery flavor.  \n\nOverall Impression – A unique cider both in terms of the story of the apple and its uncommon flavor.  Could be bumped up with a higher gravity, higher acidity apple, but interesting on its own.Total tannins=0.16%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/minkler-apple-cider-evaluation'),(196,'Apple Juice - Northwestern Greening',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Seeling apple from Iola Wisconson.  For cider - Medium body leaning towards light.  Nice acidity - not too strong, not too weak.  Easy to drink, green apple flavor with a note of pine.  Little to no noticeable tannins.\n\nOverall Impression - Exceptionally drinkable cider.  Light and refreshing. Total tannins=0.09%.\n\nhttps://brixcider.com/northwest-greening-apple-cider-evaluation'),(197,'Apple Juice - Perry Russet',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Seeling apple from Iola Wisconson.  For cider -  Medium body.  High acidity dominates the flavor, like “biting into a lemon” though there is nothing particularly citric about it.  Long, tart, dry finish.  No noticeable bitterness but some astringency.\n\nOverall Impression – A good cider apple overall.  Probably too tart on its own for most palettes, but the acidity and moderate astringency would lend well to a blend. Total tannins=0.19%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/perry-russet'),(198,'Apple Juice - Pitmaston Pineapple',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Old English heiloom.  For cider - Medium body.  Impressively tart.  Like pineapple juice without any sugar.  Brisk, full flavor.  Long, tart finish.  Little noticeable tannins.\n\nOverall Impression - A distinctive cider.  Too acidic on its own for some palettes.  Would liven up a blend with some tropical tang. Total tannins=0.10%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/pitmaston-pineapple-apple-cider-evaluation'),(199,'Apple Juice - Plumb Cider',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Origin unknown, pleasant and juicy.  For cider - Medium body.  Medium to high acidity.  Lightly drying and mildly bitter.  Long, dry finish with lingering acidity and bitterness.\n\nOverall Impression - Very good cider on its own.  Nice balance of acidity and tannins. Total tannins=0.15%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/plumb-cider'),(200,'Apple Juice - Raven',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Rich dark plum colored apple from Washington state  For cider - Medium body.  Very tart, like cranberry juice.  Long finish.  Little to no noticeable tannins.  \n\nOverall Impression - Great apple for bumping up the acidity of a blend.  Full tart flavor. Total tannins=0.09%.\n\nFor more info see - https://brixcider.com/raven'),(201,'Apple Juice - Grimes Golden',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Heirloom apple.  For cider - Green apple skin.  Even tart flavor from start to finish.  Mild bitterness and astringency. Distinctly \"green apple\" cider.  Refreshing, balanced.  Very good on its own.  Total tannins=0.12%.\n\nFor more info see: https://brixcider.com/grimes-golden-apple-cider-evaluation'),(202,'Wine Grape Juice - 25 Brix',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Pressed grape juice for wine making.  Sugar level at 25 brix.  Edit the details->name of the ingredient to specify grape variety or blend'),(203,'Candi Sugar, Amber',1,2,0.453592,3,0.00,0,'Crystalized Candi Sugar (Sucrose) used in many Belgian Tripels, Dubbels, and holiday ales.  Adds head retention and sweet aroma to beer.  Darker variants also add color.'),(204,'Candi Sugar, Dark',1,2,0.453592,3,0.00,0,'Crystalized Candi Sugar (Sucrose) used in many Belgian Tripels, Dubbels, and holiday ales.  Adds head retention and sweet aroma to beer.  Darker variants also add color.'),(205,'Caramunich II (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'German crystal malt.  Adds maltiness, aroma, color.'),(206,'Caramunich III (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'German crystal malt.  Adds maltiness, body, aroma and color.'),(207,'Caramunich Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Caramel, copper colored malt.  Used in Belgian ales and German bocks.'),(208,'Carared',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Adds body, color and improves head retention.\nAlso called \"Crystal\" malt.'),(209,'Carared (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Medium crystal malt, adds a body and reddish color.  Red ales and lagers, Scottish ales. Full body and aroma, deep red colour'),(210,'Caravienne Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Light Belgian crystal malt.  Used in light Trappist and Abbey style Belgian ales.'),(211,'Carawheat (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Used in wheat beers and ales.  A wheat version of crystal malt.  Promotes fuller flavor, wheat malt  aroma and enhanced color.'),(212,'Cherries - Black',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Black cherries are sweet but don\'t hold up as well as tart cherry to fermentation.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(213,'Cherries - Tart',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Whole fruit.  Tart cherries provide more structure/flavor and acidity in the finished beverage and are better in beer, mead, ciders.  Generally you want to freeze first, then thaw and crush before use.  Recommend using a large grain bag to contain the fruit for easy removal.\n\nNote:: SRM color is a very rough estimate.'),(214,'Chocolate Malt',1,2,0.226796,3,0.00,0,'Dark malt that gives a rich red or brown color and nutty flavor.\nUse for: Brown ales, porters, some stouts\nMaintains some malty flavor, not as dark as roasted malt.'),(215,'Chocolate Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Dark malt that gives a rich red or brown color and nutty flavor.\nUse for: Brown ales, porters, some stouts\nMaintains some malty flavor, not as dark as roasted malt.'),(216,'Chocolate Rye (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Roasted malt made with a rye base.  Adds aroma, flavor and color.  Used in rye styles.'),(217,'Chocolate Rye Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Primarily used for color and aroma in top-fermented specialty beers.'),(218,'Chocolate Wheat (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Chocholate malt made with a wheat base.  Adds aroma and color.  Alts and dark wheat beers.'),(219,'Caramunich I (Weyermann)',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'German crystal malt.  Adds maltiness, flavor, color and aroma. '),(220,'Chocolate Wheat Malt',1,2,0,3,0.00,0,'Intensifies aroma and color in top-fermented beers such as dark wheat beers.'),(221,'Corn Sugar (Dextrose)',1,2,0,3